  abstract = {The goal of noisy high-dimensional phase retrieval is to estimate an $s$-sparse parameter $\boldsymbolβ^*ın ℝ^d$ from $n$ realizations of the model $Y = (\boldsymbolX^⊤ \boldsymbolβ^*)^2 + ɛ$. Based on this model, we propose a significant semi-parametric generalization called misspecified phase retrieval (MPR), in which $Y = f(\boldsymbolX^⊤\boldsymbolβ^*, ɛ)$ with unknown $f$ and $øperatornameCov(Y, (\boldsymbolX^⊤\boldsymbolβ^*)^2) > 0$. For example, MPR encompasses $Y = h(|\boldsymbolX^⊤ \boldsymbolβ^*|) + ɛ$ with increasing $h$ as a special case. Despite the generality of the MPR model, it eludes the reach of most existing semi-parametric estimators. In this paper, we propose an estimation procedure, which consists of solving a cascade of two convex programs and provably recovers the direction of $\boldsymbolβ^*$. Our theory is backed up by thorough numerical results.},
